::: {#introduction .section .level1 number="1"}
[1]{.header-section-number} Introduction
========================================

The goal of this project is to determine the relationship between
commuting to Wallonia communes as a dependent variable and life
expectancy, age average, unemployment rate, percentage of non-Belgians,
and total population in 2013.

First, collect all of the libraries that are required for this project.

::: {#the-commute-between-wallinias-commune-in-2013 .section .level3 number="1.1.6"}
### [1.1.6]{.header-section-number} The commute between Wallinia's commune in 2013

According to my project goal, the difference between "zone out" and
"zone in" gives me the net number of people who commute to another
commune for work.As previously stated, This variable is determined as a
dependence variable.

::: {#cb12 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
Wa_commute<-read.csv("Data/Commute2013.csv",header = TRUE,
                     sep = ",",quote = "\"",dec=",",fill = TRUE,comment.char = "")
wa_commute262<-data.frame("Code_INS"=WID,"Out"=0,"In"=0)
#Creating a data frame for the net zone out of commute with a shared field for merging to a shapefile and an independence variable
for (i in WID){
  wa_commute262[wa_commute262$Code_INS==i,"Out"]<- sum(Wa_commute[Wa_commute$zonout==i,"mouv"])
  wa_commute262[wa_commute262$Code_INS==i,"In"]<- sum(Wa_commute[Wa_commute$zonin==i,"mouv"])
}
wa_commute262$Net_out<-wa_commute262$Out-wa_commute262$In
```
:::
:::

::: {#cleaning-the-data .section .level2 number="1.2"}
[1.2]{.header-section-number} Cleaning the data
-----------------------------------------------

In this subchapter, as a cleaning data base, focus on providing data
with some function that contains all the data required for analysis.

::: {#cb18 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
#mereg the shape file with independence and dependence variable
Wa_sp_01<-merge(Wallonie_sp,c(wa_commute262,Wa_unemp,Wa_NonBelges,Wa_pop,Wa_age,Wa_life,Wa_NonBelges),
                by='Code_INS')
```

::: {#the-choropleth-maps-for-the-unemployment-rate-in-2013-for-wallonie .section .level3 number="1.2.2"}
### [1.2.2]{.header-section-number} The choropleth maps for the unemployment rate in 2013 for Wallonie

::: {#cb20 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
choro <- function(shp, variable,cls,rang) {
var <- round(Wa_sp_01@data[, variable], digits = 2)
breaks <- classIntervals(var, n = cls, style = "fisher")$brk
my_colours <- brewer.pal(cls, rang)
plot(shp, col = my_colours[findInterval(var, breaks, all.inside = TRUE)],
axes = FALSE, border = rgb(1, 0.8, 0.8))
invisible(list(b = breaks, c = my_colours))
}
breaks <- choro(Wa_sp_01, "chomage_15_64_2013",8,"RdPu")
legend(x = 17991, y = 109072, legend = leglabs(breaks$b), fill = breaks$c, bty = "n")
title("Unemployment rate in 2013 for Wallonie")
```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

### [2.1.1]{.header-section-number} univariate descriptive statistics

The character values in 'Code INS' provide the ID code for each commune
in Wallonia's Regoin. The remaining six variables have integer values
and provide data on "Net out", "chomage\_15\_64 2013 (total unemployment
rate)", "Total population 2013", "Part non belges 2013", "Age moyen2013"
and "e0 .ans (Life expectancy)". According to our observations, the Net
out shows the difference between zone Out and zone In is available for
all municipalities in 2013.

::: {#cb38 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
#Computing Local Moranâs I
coordWa<-coordinates(Wa_sp_01)
```

::: {#moran-test-of-the-independent-variable .section .level3 number="2.2.1"}
### [2.2.1]{.header-section-number} Moran test of the independent variable

I\<0 ----\> negative spatial autocorrelation, So it means that the
variable of "unemployment rate" is significantly spatially dispersed,is
not significantly different from zero. (Alpha=1%).

::: {#cb39 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
moranI_unemploymentrate<-moran.test(Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013,listw = kn8_WM,zero.policy = T)
moranI_unemploymentrate
```
:::

    ## 
    ##  Moran I test under randomisation
    ## 
    ## data:  Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013  
    ## weights: kn8_WM    
    ## 
    ## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 0.067732, p-value = 0.473
    ## alternative hypothesis: greater
    ## sample estimates:
    ## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
    ##      -0.001862570      -0.003831418       0.000844964

This plot illustrate almost the negetive autocorelation.

::: {#cb41 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}

```
:::

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}
\#\#\# Local Moran (LISA) for dependent variable

LISA (or Local Moran) is the result of the lag and the variable itself
(normalized). LISA values can be easily determined using the Moran
scatterplot.The red color shows high and blue color shows low
souurounded with the same value of neighbourhood.So, The red color
represents high and the blue color represents low value that
surroundings with the neighborhood with same value.

::: {#cb42 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
dev_unemploymentrate<-Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013-mean(Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013) #express variable as deviation to mean
spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<-lag.listw(kn8_WM,dev_unemploymentrate) #lag the deviation to mean
#morlm <- lm(spatial_lag_dev_x ~ dev_x)
#morlm_itcpt<- morlm$coefficients[1]
#morlm_i <- morlm$coefficients[2] #retrieves the slope
#morlm_i
lm_dev_unemploymentrate<-localmoran(Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013,listw = kn8_WM,zero.policy = T)
lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<-as.data.frame(lm_dev_unemploymentrate)
quad_dev_unemploymentrate <- vector(mode="numeric",length=length(Wa_sp_01$Net_out))
quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <0 & spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<0] <- 1 #LL
quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <0 & spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate>0] <- 2 #LH
quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate >0 & spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<0] <- 3 #HL
quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate >0 &spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate>0] <- 4 #HH

lisa_dev_unemploymentrate$quad<-quad_dev_unemploymentrate
# statistical significance level
signif <- 0.1

lisa_dev_unemploymentrate$signif_quad<-quad_dev_unemploymentrate
lisa_dev_unemploymentrate$signif_quad[lisa_dev_unemploymentrate[,5]>signif]<-0

brks <- c(0,1,2,3,4)
colorsLISA <- c("white","blue",rgb(0,0,1,alpha=0.4),rgb(1,0,0,alpha=0.4),"red")
colorsLISA_each<-colorsLISA[findInterval(lisa_dev_unemploymentrate$signif_quad,brks,all.inside=FALSE)]
plot(Wa_sp_01,border="lightgray",col=colorsLISA_each)
box()
legend("bottomright", legend=c("insignificant","low-low","low-high","high-low","high-high"),
       fill=colorsLISA,
       bty="n", cex=0.7,y.intersp=1,x.intersp=1)

title(paste("LISA Cluster Map", signif))
```

::: {#ordinary-least-squares-ols-model .section .level2 number="2.3"}
[2.3]{.header-section-number} Ordinary least-squares (OLS) model
----------------------------------------------------------------

According to this model, the unemployment rate, age average, and life
expectancy have no significant impact at the confidence level of
95%.And, the total population has a significant impact at the confidence
level of 99%.

According to the coefficients of the model, we can say that: by having
controll on other variables when he population increases by 1 unit, the
difference between zoning out and zoning in Wallonia's commune decrease
by 1.122e-01.

Also, by having controll on other variables when the percentage of
non\_Belgian increases by 1 %, the difference between zoning out and
zoning in Wallonia's commune increase by 5.682e+01.

as well as this model The considered (and significant) variables explain
approximately 58 percent of net zoning out.

::: {#cb55 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
model_01<- lm(Wa_sp_01$Net_out~ Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013+Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013+Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013+Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013+Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013+Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans.,na.action = na.omit)
summary(model_01)
```

::: {#spatial-chractrestic-of-variable .section .level1 number="3"}
[3]{.header-section-number} spatial chractrestic of variable
============================================================

there is two way for considering the results of the Moran's I test on
the dependent variable: 1.spatial dependency 2.spatial heterogeneity

::: {#lagrange-multiplier-diagnostics-for-spatial-dependence .section .level2 number="3.1"}
[3.1]{.header-section-number} Lagrange multiplier diagnostics for spatial dependence
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LMerr = 10.249, df = 1, p-value = 0.001367--------\> p-value is smaller
than alpha=0.01, This result demonstrates that the two Moran' I result
tests are correct. and residuals are spatially dependent.

RLMerr = 32.655, df = 1, p-value = 1.1e-08--------\> p-value is smaller
than alpha=0.01.So, there is spatialy dependency in errors.

LMlag = 1.865, df = 1, p-value = 0.172------------\> p-value is larger
than alpha=0.01.So, there is not a spatial dependency.

RLMlag = 24.271, df = 1, p-value = 8.369e-07------\>p-value is larger
than alpha=0.01.So,there is not a spatial dependency in errors.

SARMA = 34.52, df = 2, p-value = 3.192e-08--------\>p-value is larger
than alpha=0.01.So,there is not a spatial dependency.

::: {#cb66 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
LMOLS <-lm.LMtests(model_01,kn8_WM,test=c("LMerr", "RLMerr","LMlag","RLMlag", "SARMA"),zero.policy = T)
LMOLS
```

In this model compared to the OLS model, the variables of total
population and presentage of non-Belgians are not significant. But the
negative relationship between total population and net zoning out is the

presentage of non-Belgian.

::: {#gwr-using-gwmodel .section .level2 number="4.1"}
[4.1]{.header-section-number} GWR using GWModel
-----------------------------------------------

GWR analyzes a local model of the parameter or method you are attempting
to comprehend or predict by connecting a regression model to each
feature in the dataset.

::: {#cb82 .sourceCode}
``` {.sourceCode .r}
DepVar<-"Net_out"
IndVars1<- c("Total_population_2013","chomage_15_64_2013" , "Part_non_belges_2013", "Age_moyen2013", "e0_.ans.")
model.sel <- model.selection.gwr(DepVar,IndVars1,data=Wa_sp_01,kernel="bisquare",adaptive = TRUE, bw=20)
```
:::

::: {#conclusion .section .level2 number="4.5"}
[4.5]{.header-section-number} Conclusion
----------------------------------------

In this project, the net zoning out of communes with the goal of
commuting was considered as an independence variable, and the
unemployment rate, average age, life expectancy, total population, and
percentage of non-Belgians in 2013 as a dependent variable.The total
population and the percentage of non-Belgians have an effect on the
independence variable in the OLS model.

According to the coefficients of the model, we can say that: by having
controll on other variables when he population increases by 1 unit, the
difference between zoning out and zoning in Wallonia's commune decrease
by 1.122e-01. Also, by having controll on other variables when the
percentage of non\_Belgian increases by 1 %, the difference between
zoning out and zoning in Wallonia's commune increase by 5.682e+01.

As a result, the percentage of non-Belgians has a positive relationship
with the independent variable, while the total population has a negative
relationship.

Significant spatial error dependence, significant spatial lag
dependence, and no significant spatial error dependence after accounting
for spatial lag dependence were discovered in spatial dependence.

The lower AICc value in the local model (4685.144) than in the global
(OLS) model (4717.739), as well as the higher R-squared value in the
local model (0.57) than in the global (OLS) model (0.67), confirm the
existence of spatial variation in the relationships between two
variables.

In the point pattern part the number of child care places is represented
by a circle. In addition, the size of the circle indicates the number of
places in each commune.(using leaflet for illustrating the point in the
certain place)
